In [30]:
for i, row in data1_cleaned.iterrows():
    if (abs(row["diff_21_22"]) > 40) and (abs(row["diff_22_23"]) > 40):
        data1_cleaned.at[i, '2022'] = row['2022'] / 10 if row["diff_21_22"] > 0 else row['2022'] * 10
    elif (abs(row["diff_21_22"]) > 40) and (abs(row["diff_22_23"]) < 40):
        data1_cleaned.at[i, '2021'] = row['2021'] * 10 if row["diff_21_22"] > 0 else row['2021'] / 10
    elif (abs(row["diff_21_22"]) < 40) and (abs(row["diff_22_23"]) > 40):
        data1_cleaned.at[i, '2023'] = row['2023'] / 10 if row['diff_22_23'] > 0 else row['2023'] * 10
    else:
        data1_cleaned.at[i, '2023'] = row["2023"]
        data1_cleaned.at[i, '2022'] = row["2022"]
        data1_cleaned.at[i, '2021'] = row["2021"]

DATA VISUALIZATION¶

The Best and Worst AQI Values in The World¶

What is AQI ?¶

The Air Quality Index (AQI) is a tool for reporting daily air quality. It tells you how clean or polluted your air is and what associated health effects might be a concern for you. The AQI focuses on health effects you may experience within a few hours or days after breathing polluted air.

First, we want to display the 10 cities with the lowest AQI values in 2023 and compare them with the previous year

In [49]:
India_AQI = data1_cleaned[data1_cleaned['country'].isin(['India'])].sort_values(by = '2023', ascending=True)

species = India_AQI['city'].values
values_2022 = India_AQI['2022'].values
values_2023 = India_AQI['2023'].values

mean_value_2023 = values_2023.mean()

# Plotting
width = 1.05
ind = range(len(species))

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

colors = ['#2D9596' if value <= mean_value_2023 else '#EF4040' for value in values_2023]

plt.bar(ind, values_2023, width, label='2023', color=colors)

plt.axhline(y=mean_value_2023, color='#200E3A', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5, label='mean')

plt.xlabel('City')
plt.ylabel('Values')
plt.title('Values by City and Year')
plt.xticks(ind, species, rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
